Workshop on \xe2\x80\x9cPromotion of Development and Investment of ICT Sector in Nepal" organized by the Investment Board Nepal in collaboration with the Japan International Cooperation Agency (JICA) and brought together key stakeholders from the government, private sector, and academia to discuss strategies to accelerate investment in Nepal's rapidly growing ICT industry. 

Here\xe2\x80\x99s some of the key takeaways from the discussions:

- Software development, data centers, digital payments and e-commerce have strong potential as high-growth investment areas within Nepal's ICT sector. 

- Policy reforms around taxation, data regulations, and digital infrastructure are needed to boost innovation and create an enabling environment for both domestic and foreign tech investment.

- Public-private partnerships can play a crucial role in developing future-ready talent pipelines and research capabilities in new technologies like AI, IoT and cybersecurity. 

- With our young, tech-savvy population and growing mobile/internet penetration, Nepal offers unique advantages as an emerging ICT/BPO hub in South Asia.

With continued collaboration between government agencies, private firms and academia, Nepal's ICT sector is poised for robust, inclusive growth in the years ahead. 

Kudos to the Investment Board Nepal and JICA for organizing this timely event on a sector that offers immense potential to boost jobs and economic development in Nepal!

Nepal\xe2\x80\x99s Hindutva Moment
by Shubhanga Pandey
\xe2\x80\x9cA little over a decade after Nepal declared itself a secular republic, religious identity threatens to emerge as a new axis of polarization in the politics of the former Hindu kingdom. 

A string of incidents that transpired over the past year have rudely awakened many in Nepal \xe2\x80\x94 including its complacent public sphere \xe2\x80\x94 of the inroads made by activist networks of militant Hindu nationalists, particularly in towns close to Nepal\xe2\x80\x99s long border with India. In August of last year, clips of a group publicly feasting on beef in Dharan, a city in eastern Nepal, gathered much national outrage, as eating bovine meat is largely taboo in the country and oxen slaughter remains illegal. 

This rabble-rousing tactic of activists, who were opposed to this law, triggered swift street mobilization by several Hindu groups in protest, who linked this incident to an already existing controversy in the city involving the setting up of a church opposite a Hindu temple. However, the potentially violent confrontation was foiled after the local administration temporarily restrained the protesters\xe2\x80\x99 movement.
